V5fTi0o1eNovvQJTD%2FZvrWoLRG1FeALXLvBsTdgDbf9lqXhe3fB0XlJdjK%2BL9uSaSkpEsK4E%2BPOG6XuOebpwZ60vuk0pT%2BkzuEJgR%2BjrFklb5h99cr%2FetOyp3YFvfzz8AQ9ORcZjuz1LFjp0zsrj%2FrP7peh%2Bbmsvrm9%2Ffnuz621ObLugm6JFeXuNTRNDFvo2tXIXjhL0iqr0WXL0%2BD81QYtQ" id="w1_2_5_7_8_9"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#eeb3b3;strokeColor=#c0392b;fontColor=#5a1410;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="1296" y="752" width="395" height="140" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Net-negative lives&lt;br&gt;(animal suffering dominates)&lt;br&gt;[1+2+5+7+8+9+10]&lt;br&gt;→ Shrimp Welfare Project&lt;br&gt;   198k lives-eq/$1k · 60% best&lt;br&gt;   runner-up Wild insects (humane pesticides) · 40%&lt;br&gt;(Brian Tomasik, David Benatar)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + future_humans_matter_with_discounting + animals_matter_a_lot + suffering_focused + meat_eater_problem + net_negative_animal_lives&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The net-negative-lives hypothesis: factory-farmed and wild animals endure more suffering than wellbeing, so their lives are not worth living. Reducing that suffering is worth more per dollar (you are mitigating a catastrophe, not improving a good life), most of all for the astronomical wild-invertebrate populations. Combined with the meat-eater problem it drives human charities firmly net-negative — every human sustained means more net-negative farmed lives. Presupposes counting wild/invertebrate animals, so it requires animals_matter_a_lot; and like the meat-eater problem it is a near-term animal get-off point, not combined with astronomical-stakes longtermism (no_discounting_future_humans). || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 5 future_humans_matter_with_discounting → 7 animals_matter_a_lot → 8 suffering_focused → 9 meat_eater_problem → 10 net_negative_animal_lives" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJytWG1v2zgS%2FiuD4PbO7jqKJL8nlwPSxtktNu0WSXrFoilUW