label="Net-negative lives&lt;br&gt;(animal suffering dominates)&lt;br&gt;[1+2+5+7+8+10]&lt;br&gt;→ Shrimp Welfare Project&lt;br&gt;   198k lives-eq/$1k · 60% best&lt;br&gt;   runner-up Wild insects (humane pesticides) · 40%&lt;br&gt;(Brian Tomasik, David Benatar)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + future_humans_matter_with_discounting + animals_matter_a_lot + suffering_focused + net_negative_animal_lives&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The net-negative-lives hypothesis: factory-farmed and wild animals endure more suffering than wellbeing, so their lives are not worth living. Reducing that suffering is worth more per dollar (you are mitigating a catastrophe, not improving a good life), most of all for the astronomical wild-invertebrate populations. Combined with the meat-eater problem it drives human charities firmly net-negative — every human sustained means more net-negative farmed lives. Presupposes counting wild/invertebrate animals, so it requires animals_matter_a_lot; and like the meat-eater problem it is a near-term animal get-off point, not combined with astronomical-stakes longtermism (no_discounting_future_humans). || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 5 future_humans_matter_with_discounting → 7 animals_matter_a_lot → 8 suffering_focused → 10 net_negative_animal_lives" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJylWG1z27gR%2Fis7nl4rpTJFUu9y3Rkllu8y5%2BQyttObmyijQCQkoSYJFgBN63K%2B394FQEqUrdRM9cUDi8Czz75iF19PQrokWaTe8JCejE%2FabTg%2FP4dbQVgCikMgyO8bXOQJzDLf9bqQcxGF94zmkHtzf96bD%2BbDuedCQyqeguc2NcAsQaCJlFmcKsYTCNaINwYXUiJ4sGYk0nDeyAcPlkTMSU4283UWk0SWH3wgCYtJJOeSxzRfE1V%2B6cEyU5mgxYF5TJSiYp4ztZ6HTAY8SxRLVuX2wRao2EjmEd%2BCDUFmyyUVeGC%2B5EEmabil5kJC1TyhK6LYPZ1bmHmEa2kUnJJgDWSnJZNA4MNGrXG9ZBEFtOHus2yD0lqQMJQtEBQNzxIqgQsDJugpGofEFCkyib%2BrNbV2%2B5tEhZPAYJxBwOOUS63fdgOeTUKKiPgTs9SkIklIIp5QiNGzkQNfto6b3n%2FRVPVx%2BpDSQOHBexJlFPjSIOx87Biw11QqWGQbyLQYfVDSqmJjuFkLFqfwK43QmxQ%2BCP5vxLWnf5y%2Bn15PbqcXsN