FAPPDgVG4%2FN5ixZaCGclxfGR%2FdTcX%2FeHf3%2Bd%2FfLm9vd7TixF46%2BVhflR0C8dhmy0B%2BlKp8U0YJeUbU%2BS84e%2FwM7fJKJ" id="w1_2_5_7_9_18"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#c9b3dd;strokeColor=#4a2a78;fontColor=#201040;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="2603" y="1434" width="395" height="140" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Net-negative lives&lt;br&gt;(animal suffering dominates)&lt;br&gt;[1+2+5+7+10]&lt;br&gt;→ Shrimp Welfare Project&lt;br&gt;   64k lives-eq/$1k · 59% best&lt;br&gt;   runner-up Wild insects (humane pesticides) · 41%&lt;br&gt;(Brian Tomasik, David Benatar)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + future_humans_matter_with_discounting + animals_matter_a_lot + net_negative_animal_lives&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The net-negative-lives hypothesis: factory-farmed and wild animals endure more suffering than wellbeing, so their lives are not worth living. Reducing that suffering is worth more per dollar (you are mitigating a catastrophe, not improving a good life), most of all for the astronomical wild-invertebrate populations. Combined with the meat-eater problem it drives human charities firmly net-negative — every human sustained means more net-negative farmed lives. Presupposes counting wild/invertebrate animals, so it requires animals_matter_a_lot; and like the meat-eater problem it is a near-term animal get-off point, not combined with astronomical-stakes longtermism (no_discounting_future_humans). || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 5 future_humans_matter_with_discounting → 7 animals_matter_a_lot → 10 net_negative_animal_lives" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJylWG1v2zYQ%2FiuHYC9258iS%2FO4uA9LG6YqlXZGkGIa6cGmJtrlKlEZSUbwu%2B%2B07kpItxwpiwF9axTo%2B99wb707fTkK6IFmkXichPRmftNtwdnYGt4IwDiqBQJB%2F1viQc5hmvut1IU9EFN4xmkPuzfxZbzaYeS40pEpS8NymPj7lCHMuZRaniiUcghWijcGFlIgkWDESaTBv5IMHCyJmJCfr2SqLCZflCx8IZzGJ5EwmMc1XRJVverDIVCZocWA